    <!-- Content Section 2: Shirvanshahs Palace -->
    <div class="content-section">
        <div class="round-frame">
            <div>
                <h2>Shirvanshahs Palace</h2>
                <p>The Shirvanshahs' Palace is a former residence with a complex that includes the palace, Divan-Khane, and more. It is part of UNESCO’s World Heritage List and a pearl of Azerbaijani architecture.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="image-container">
        <img src="ширван ночь.jpeg" alt="Shirvanshahs Palace" width="400" height="200">
    </div>
<!-- Content Section 3: Maiden Tower -->
<div class="content-section">
    <div class="round-frame">
        <div>
            <h2>Maiden Tower</h2>
            <p>Maiden Tower (Qız Qalası) is an ancient fortress building near the coastal part of Icheri-Sheher. It is one of the most important components of the seaside “facade” of Baku. The tower stands on a rock, its height is 28 meters above sea level. The tower is included in the UNESCO World Heritage List. There are many legends around the Maiden Tower, all of which are very interesting.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="image-container">
    <img src="qizqalasi.jpg" alt="Maiden Tower" width="350" height="350">
    <img src="qiz 2.jpg" alt="Maiden Tower" width="350" height="350">
</div>

<!-- Content Section 4: Heydar Aliyev Center -->
<div class="content-section">
    <div class="round-frame">
        <div>
            <h2>Heydar Aliyev Centre</h2>
            <p>Heydar Aliyev Center (Heydər Əliyev Mərkəzi) is a cultural center located on Heydar Aliyev Avenue in Baku, the capital of Azerbaijan. The center is a complex building that includes an auditorium, museum, exhibition halls, and administrative offices. The center was designed in 2007 by architect Zaha Hadid. The Heydar Aliyev Cultural Center is considered one of the symbols of modern Baku.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="image-container">
    <img src="Гейдар снаружи.jpg" alt="Heydar Aliyev Center" width="300" height="300">
    <img src="Гейдар изнутри.jpg" alt="Heydar Aliyev Center" width="300" height="300">
</div>
<!-- Content Section 5: Museum of Modern Art -->
<div class="content-section">
    <div class="round-frame">
        <div>
            <h2>Museum of Modern Art</h2>
            <p>
                The Museum of Modern Art (Müasir İncəsənət muzeyi) contains over 800 works by Azerbaijani artists and sculptors, mostly working in the avant-garde style.
                The museum exhibits works by such masters as Sattar Bahlulzade, Beyukaga Mirzazade, Elmira Shahtakhtinskaya, Tair Salahov, Omar Eldarov, Nadir Abdurakhmanov, Gennady Brizhatyuk, and many others. A separate hall exhibits works by representatives of Western avant-gardism Salvador Dali, Pablo Picasso, and Marc Chagall.
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="image-container">
    <img src="museum 344.jpg" alt="Museum of Modern Art" width="300" height="300">
    <img src="museum of art 2.jpg" alt="Museum of Modern Art" width="300" height="300">
</div>

<!-- Content Section 6: Azerbaijan National Carpet Museum -->
<div class="content-section">
    <div class="round-frame">
        <div>
            <h2>Azerbaijan National Carpet Museum</h2>
            <p>
                Azerbaijan National Carpet Museum (Azərbaycan milli xalça muzeyi) is a museum of Azerbaijan dedicated to carpet weaving, one of the oldest types of decorative and applied arts of the country.
                Carpet weaving is one of the oldest types of decorative-applied art of Azerbaijan. The data of archeological researches carried out in the territory of the state testify that the art of carpet weaving originated in Azerbaijan in ancient times.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="image-container">
    <img src="ковры.jpg" alt="Azerbaijan National Carpet Museum" width="300" height="300">
    <img src="ковры.jpeg" alt="Azerbaijan National Carpet Museum" width="300" height="300">
</div>
<!-- Content Section 7: Flame Towers -->
<div class="content-section">
    <div class="round-frame">
        <div>
            <h2>Flame Towers</h2>
            <p>
                The Flame Towers (Alov qüllələri) are a group of three skyscrapers in Baku. The three flame-shaped towers are intended to symbolize the elements of fire and are a reference to Azerbaijan's nickname "The Land of Fire",
                historically rooted in a region where natural gas flares emit from the ground and Zoroastrian worshipers considered flames to be a symbol of the divine.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="image-container">
    <img src="flame.jpg" alt="Flame Towers" width="300" height="300">
    <img src="flame456y7u8.webp" alt="Flame Towers" width="300" height="300">
</div>

<!-- Content Section 8: Little Venice -->
<div class="content-section">
    <div class="round-frame">
        <div>
            <h2>Little Venice</h2>
            <p>
                Little Venice (Kiçik Venesiya) is a system of recreational water canals located in the capital of Azerbaijan, Baku,
                on the territory of the seaside boulevard. “Little Venice” has existed since 1960, is a landmark of the seaside park,
                and is considered a favorite place of recreation for visitors to the park.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
<div class="image-container">
    <img src="little 2.jpg" alt="Little Venice" width="400" height="200">
    <img src="venice.jpeg" alt="Little Venice" width="400" height="200">
</div>
<!-- Content Section 9: Baku Eye -->
<div class="content-section">
    <div class="round-frame">
        <div>
            <h2>Baku Eye</h2>
            <p>
                Baku Eye (Şeytan çarxı) is a 60-meter-high Ferris wheel located in Baku city, in the new boulevard part of the Seaside National Park, 
                stretching to the State Flag Square. It was built by Dutch Wheels, a Dutch company, in 2014.
            </p>
            <p>
                When you are 60 meters above sea level, you have an unforgettable view of the most beautiful city.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
